article.description:
Louisiana State kicked off the new year with the same
old results.
article.headline: Big first half key as LSU again wins by at least 30
article.linkText: Another easy win pushes No. 3 LSU to 11-0 start
article.story:
DENTON, Texas (AP) -- Louisiana State kicked off the new year with the same
old results.

	   Aiysha Smith scored 14 of her 16 points in the first half, and LSU (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today; No. 2 Associated Press) continued its best start in six years by beating
North Texas 74-43 Thursday night.

	   LSU (11-0) won its first 14 games in the 1996-1997
season. North Texas (4-6) has lost four in a row and six of
its past seven games.

	   LSU has won six games by more than 30 points this season.

	   ''I warned our team that this was a very dangerous game,'' LSU
coach Sue Gunter said. ''North Texas has beaten a lot of good teams
at home, and I made our kids very aware of that.''

	   Smith was mindful of her coach's word as she connected on
seven of 11 shots in the first half, and LSU held a 35-18 lead at the
break.

	   Heather Trout hit a free throw to pull North Texas to 40-25
early in the second half. But LSU went on a 19-4 run to make it
59-29.

	   Crystal White capped the run with six consecutive points, and the
Lady Eagles got no closer than 24 thereafter.

	   ''We didn't handle their defensive pressure well,'' North Texas
coach Tina Slinker said. ''We were just out of sync offensively.''

	   Wendlyn Jones added 15 points for LSU, and Seimone Augustus
scored 12 while grabbing seven rebounds. White scored 10 points off
the bench.

	   Emily Britt and Vilma Grismanauskaite paced North Texas with 10
points each.

	   The Lady Tigers hit 51 percent of their shots from the field (32-for-63).

	   LSU, which has not allowed an opponent to score 60 points in its past 10 games, held North Texas to just 24-percent shooting
(18-for-74).

	   North Texas also committed a season-high 26 turnovers.

	   ''Our team defense was the key,'' Jones said. ''We had a couple
of early breakdowns, but otherwise we were pretty solid.''

	   North Texas was 4-for-25 from the field in the first 15 minutes
as LSU took a 27-8 lead.

	   ''We've never seen defensive pressure like that,'' Britt said.
''It caught us off guard and we forced some shots early.''

	   The Lady Eagles crept to 27-14 on Jasmine Williams' layup, but
LSU stretched its lead back to 19 by scoring the next
six points.

	   LSU center DeTrina White did not play because of a sore right
foot. She is expected to return for the Lady Tigers' game Saturday
against Penn State.
